<subSubSection pageId="602" pageNumber="603" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="602" pageNumber="603">
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1853" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Lachnocrepis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="602" pageNumber="603" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lachnocrepis</taxonomicName>
LeConte, 1853c: 391. Type species: 
<taxonomicName class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Oodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="602" pageNumber="603" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parallelus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="602" pageNumber="603">Oodes parallelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Say, 1830 by monotypy. Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="602" pageNumber="603">lachnos</emphasis>
(soft hair, down) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="602" pageNumber="603">crepis</emphasis>
(boot, sandal), alluding to the presence of dense hairs underneath all tarsomeres (&quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="602" pageNumber="603">tarsi omnes subtus pilosi</emphasis>
&quot;) of the adult [feminine].
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="602" pageNumber="603">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Habu" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Eulachnocrepis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="602" pageNumber="603" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Eulachnocrepis</taxonomicName>
Habu, 1956b: 96. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1873" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Oodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="602" pageNumber="603" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prolixus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="602" pageNumber="603">Oodes prolixus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bates, 1873 by original designation. Synonymy established by Bousquet (1996a: 467). Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="602" pageNumber="603">eu</emphasis>
(agreeable, original, primitive) and the generic name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1853" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Lachnocrepis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="602" pageNumber="603" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="602" pageNumber="603">Lachnocrepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="602" pageNumber="603">q.v</emphasis>
.] [feminine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="602" pageNumber="603" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="602" pageNumber="603">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="602" pageNumber="603">Three species in temperate regions of North America (one species) and eastern Asia (two species).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
